to `JAVA_HOME` properly.\n\nBut wait - I should also consider: **JDK 17.0.12+7 from Temurin**. Is there a known issue with this specific version? \n\nActually, I think the real answer here might be simpler. Let me reconsider...\n\nThe most common Java-related error in .NET MAUI Android builds is:\n\n**`JAVA_HOME` is set but the build uses a different JDK** - The .NET Android workload installs Microsoft's build of OpenJDK 17 and uses it by default, regardless of `JAVA_HOME`. If there's a mismatch or if the Microsoft JDK isn't installed, you get errors.\n\n**The fix**: Either install the Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with the MAUI workload, or explicitly set `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in your project file to point to your Temurin installation.\n\nWithout seeing the exact error message, I'm thinking through the most likely culprits - either the build can't locate or execute the JDK, there's a version incompatibility between what the build expects and what Temurin provides, classpath issues are preventing the runtime from finding required classes, or the build system simply isn't recognizing the `JAVA_HOME` variable even though it's set. The core issue is probably that .NET MAUI Android on macOS doesn't actually use `JAVA_HOME` the way you'd expect. by default. It looks for the Microsoft OpenJDK at a hardcoded path. The fix is to either:\n\n1. Install the Microsoft OpenJDK 17 via the MAUI workload (`dotnet workload install maui`)\n2. Or set `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in your `.csproj` to point to your Temurin JDK\n\nActually wait, I want to reconsider one more time. Let me think about whether there's a specific known issue with Temurin 17.0.12...\n\nJDK 17.0.12 was released in July 2024. I'm not aware of a specific incompatibility with that exact version for MAUI builds.\n\nOK so I think the most likely answer, without seeing the exact error, is about the build system not picking up the Temurin JDK. But since the user asked \"what's wrong\", they expect me to diagnose the issue.\n\n